explanation:
UT_StubTableEntry_t — Need the struct/typedef to know the types of the members (EntryType, FuncKey). In particular, the type of FuncKey (and whether the struct is an incomplete type) determines whether the cast/assignment FuncKey = (UT_EntryKey_t)Func or the subsequent access OnceEnt->FuncKey uses any nonstandard or implementation-specific behavior.

UT_EntryKey_t — The underlying type (pointer type, integer, uintptr_t, function-pointer type, etc.) is required to decide if the cast from a function pointer (void (*)(void)) to UT_EntryKey_t is a standard, implementation-defined, or extension-only operation.

UT_StubTable — The declaration (array or pointer) is needed to confirm that pointer arithmetic ++StubPtr and iteration across UT_MAX_FUNC_STUBS is applied to an array of the declared element type and does not rely on any compiler-specific layout/extension.

UT_MAX_FUNC_STUBS — The numeric constant controlling the loop must be known to verify index/iteration assumptions and to check that code relies on any nonstandard constant expressions or compiler-specific sized arrays.

UT_ENTRYTYPE_UNUSED and UT_ENTRYTYPE_CALL_ONCE — Definitions (enum constants or macros) are required to determine if EntryType comparisons use standard integer/enum constants or any compiler-specific extensions (e.g., nonstandard enum sizing or bit-field tricks).

UtAssert_Abort — Prototype or macro/definition is required to check whether the call site uses or depends on any compiler extensions (for example, if UtAssert_Abort is a macro that expands to compiler-specific syntax or has attributes implemented via compiler extensions).

NULL — The definition of NULL (macro) may affect pointer/integer comparisons or casts; having its definition ensures the code uses the standard representation (0 or ((void*)0)) and not a compiler-specific extension.

These symbols give the necessary type, macro and declaration context to determine whether the cast and accesses in UT_Stub_CallOnce rely on compiler-specific language extensions rather than standard C.
